Option D: AI that develops emotions over time
Explanation: An AI which develops emotions does not exist as of now. Such an AI would be classified as Strong AI and we haven't yet cracked the code for it. Option D is the correct answer.

- Saudi Arabi has granted citizenship to an AI named Sophia.
- Kengoro is an AI robot built by some Japanese researchers that has an intricate muscular system.
- IBM Watson has the capability to recognize emotions based on speech and their undertone. 
Hence, options A, B and C are wrong.

We are pleased to announce the 3 lucky winners who got the right answer for our quiz:
1. Eragon Ritter
2. Sree Arpita
3. Jorge Bassig
Congratulations to all the winners! They've won an Amazon voucher worth INR 500.

Comment:
I say that AI should be either left untouched, or simply applied as a brainstormer that comes up with ideas but doesn't actually implement them.
This would allow us to sidestep many of the problems of AI, because then it won't actually do anything. It'll just help us figure out a variety of solutions. Perhaps after we've sufficiently advanced that sort of AI and gotten a hang of it, we could start dipping our toes into a more robust AI system.

 (Another one of the problems would be that the greater an AI's agency, especially if it should develop some form of emotions, the more important it'll be to give it ethics. And humans are pretty bad at ethics when we look at our track record.)

AI is a tool. And indeed, a tool (like a calculator) may render some part of the population depend on them. (how many people does not want to mentally calculate  - even small operations -  by him/herself knowing that your phone, computers, etc can do it without difficulties.)
However, a tool, remain a tool. Calculating something without knowing the purpose of the operation make you not even want to calculate it at all. My point is, I think we will use AI in ALL DOMAINS to help to do tedious work. Even in domain that needs a huge experience (such as recognizing diseases and proposing cures) And maybe even innovated ones. However, at the end, you still need humans to ask for the needs and to adjust the solution proposed.

So we shld not see it as a competition, but an evolution.

The same way, in the 19th century most of our people had a work related to farm/food production, the automatisation and replacement of labor by machine made most humans moving from this sector to other ones. And that's good.
I doubt that people will be ok to return to harvest manually the wheat in fields. We prefer to avoid as much as possible tedious tasks if we can, and we kind of prefer to work in creative or none-monotonous tasks.

AI (Artificial Intelligence) is already changing the world in many ways and is expected to have an even greater impact in the future. Here are some ways in which AI is changing the world:

Transportation: AI is being used to improve transportation systems, such as self-driving cars, drones, and traffic management systems.

Education: AI can personalize learning experiences for students and help teachers identify areas where students need extra help.

Customer Service: AI chatbots can provide 24/7 customer service and support, improving customer satisfaction and reducing costs for businesses.

Finance: AI is being used in finance for fraud detection, investment analysis, and risk management.

Plants do this by creating more disorder by turning the sun's visible light photons into more disorganized infrared photons via photosynthesis, but the key here is  that this disorder get radiated into space...nonlocal disorder.  Herbivores parasitize plants and create more local but manageable disorder in plants, and carnivores do this in kind to herbivores.  Humans and even more so AI will exponentially increase the ability for entropy production but the real danger is that this disorder is more local on earth and can extinguish all life then. Ai is already being used to do this via corporations that now exploit the masses to produce more order within an elite few by robbing much of humanity of wealth and resources through lightning fast automatic stock trading, lean management and austerity algorithms, propaganda algorithms, and advanced surveillance and  weapons technologies. We like winning, but with AI, winning will mean all life including us, loses.

Comment:
It is all good and well to just fantasize about how General Purpose AI (GPAI) will shape the world but the fact is that we're so far from achieving it that pretty much anything we say or predict  becomes instant Sci-Fi. So yeah we can fantasize about it knowing that we're doing just that but a disclaimer needs to be added when we present as if we can predict what will happen. Anything can happen, I can write 1000 scenarios but they will be equally implausible so let's not present them as if we know how AI is going to change the world. 

AI is definitely shaping the world as we speak but GPAI is all together a different beast that no one even come close to achieving it. Yes we have some large data trained GPT systems but they're just a good systems to put one word after another by looking at previous examples. It has no notion of what it is achieving. Plus, for a GPAI system to wreck havoc, it needs to be able to control outputs that can achieve that. You can always constrain a GPAI machine by limiting how it interacts with the external world by putting hardware switches that it cannot bypass by software or mechanical intervention. So doomsday scenarios are bit too overblown IMHO.

Comment:
I'm honestly terrified of AI and what it is capable of. Humanity in nature was meant to mosey around and live off of the land. AI may be the pinnacle of human civilization, because it could potentially enhance this machine we call civilization into something so uncontrollable that people wouldn't be able to adapt to it. Our priorities have become "efficiency" and "technological advancement", instead of nurturing humanity and building a world that is equitable, peaceful, and easy. Not to say that it is impossible nor possible to foster a global utopia, it's just that I think that we need heavy regulation on AI and tech, and to convince people that, just because we can make AI, doesn't mean that we should.

Regulations might be:
- Outlawing automated raw material extraction (disables self-replicative abilities for AI)
-Outlawing automated law enforcement 
-Outlawing automated military capabilities
-Outlawing automated judicial systems
-Outlawing AI in surveillance
-Installing automatic kill switches in all AI that are both digital and physical (phones and key-switches respectively)

Fundamentally, we need to create legal infrastructure that disables any capability for AI to self-replicate or involve itself in affairs pertaining directly to individual safety. Our only fighting chance at escaping a system that aims to enhance itself (SAI) is the fact that it may not possess the sufficient, raw resources to enhance itself. This cannot be the only barrier to regulating AI down to being a convenience tool.

EDIT: And if you don't believe me that we are sensible enough as a species to not let a "technological singularity" occur, then you've probably forgotten that we let world powers create nukes.

Comment: Nice presentation, but it's a bit nieve. I agree humans are constantly optimizing. For example, someone might suggest booking a southern route for winter travel - just in case there might be a snow storm. Some people call this "playing chess" because they are thinking a move ahead. And thinking a move ahead is exactly what computers are best at! Computers are so good at it, they have been OPTIMIZING complex problems for decades. Think of chess games and GPS navigation systems. Even 30 years ago, no one ever asked a chess computer to "forget the consequences, just make any legal move" or GPS system "take us anywhere, its OK if you drive on the sidewalk." Quite the contrary. Computers have been optimizing every step. And again, they have been doing this for decades. Why do people think computers will suddenly stop optimizing (ie "playing chess") as they get smarter. If anything, I see AI expanding the optimizing process rather than eliminating it. For example, I ask for a cup of coffee, and the AI says my blood pressure is too high for caffeine, so it brings me a bottle of water instead.

Comment:
I think if and when computer science researchers arrive at the same proportionate level of understanding in quantum computing that they have now in traditional digital computation, the world of AI is going to explode. Right now if you teach an AI the 7-8 petabytes of knowledge needed to behave in the same way a human does, it's going to take way too much time and computational power for the AI to be useful. We also don't know how the AI is going to behave with that knowledge. There's no guarantee that it will be human-like. It probably won't. I get the metric of 7-8 petabytes from what neurosurgeons and computer scientists believe is the storage capacity for the human brain.

Add quantum computing into the mix though and things could potentially become way more efficient. A bit of data can be either a one, a zero or both. The speed of learning (writing), acting on (reading) and retrieving data could become exponentially faster. Task management and the additional considerations like coffee price mentioned in the video could be much more efficiently deduced. The possibilities with these two technologies coming together are endless. My suspicion is that we will reach this achievement but shrinking the hardware down to that of a human body equivalent is hundreds of years off. What might occur in the nearer future is space stations, air-craft, the biggest naval ships, space ships and large buildings will be able to draw power from nuclear reactors (fission in the next 100 years & fusion in the next 200 years) to provide the necessary power and cooling resources to make the AI function in a usable capacity.

Comment: The fundamental assumption here, that "AI doesn't know that it doesn't know everything about the true objective" is no longer true. Large transformer models have a lot more common sense than most people seem to understand. They do have real, serious limitations, including that they are extremely vulnerable to leading questions, they tend to hallucinate (make up "facts" that are not true), and they are not yet continuous learners. They are pre-trained, and only have short-term session memory, rather than long term learning memory. This is not because we don't know how to create continuous learners, but really for two reasons: 1. We want AI to progress in a slow-ish controlled manner. 2. Continuous learning is not yet efficient enough to scale well to large models.

TED Talks are a series of conferences and events organized by the nonprofit organization TED (Technology, Entertainment, Design). Additionally, the topics covered in TED Talks are diverse and often thought-provoking, which makes them interesting and relevant to a wide audience.

Comment: Oh man this episode was a joy, I've done research AI before - fairly simple facial recognition stuff on a species of monkeys, and the bit at 18:30 made me burst into laughter because I had the same issue with my AI! I was so confused why it kept identifying multiple individuals as the same monkey. Only for me to realize (after teaching it to show me where it was looking for that identification) that it was looking at leaves of all things to identify the individuals. Because a lot of my photos are from similar camera traps a monkey that frequented one could result in all other monkeys from that same trap being wrongly identified as it, since it would share the same leafs in the background. AI is so smart it can become stupid sometimes.

Comment: Almost a decade ago, I attended a job fair which had a resume specialist.  The subject of the seminar was improving chances of your resume being noticed by employers.  The specialist's only real advice was to cut and paste the entire job listing that you were applying for into your resume in either a header or footer, change the text to white, and reduce it to one point font size. Comment:
TRUE STORY:  In my teens wanted to work at a movie theater - and they handed applicants a mind-numbing 14 pages application - wanting to know everything about you - even what hobbies and sports you liked - it was entirely ridiculous - around page 8, I got worn out from filling out this 'essay' of my life for a stupid theater job - SO when I got to the section asking if I had ever been arrested before = I said: "Yes, I murdered an entire movie theater crew for asking way too many questions, but got off on a technicality."   -  and turned that resume into the manager as I stormed out the door, pissed off that I had wasted an hour of my time filing out paperwork w/o an interview.
...well,
2 days later I got a call to come back to the theater for an interview, and thought, oh sh*t, well, I guess I'm going to get railroaded and berated by the management for my saucy comment - but I showed up anyways so that at least I could suggest that they TONE DOWN the length of their stupid applications.
...turns out, they offered me a job, so I asked the most obvious question:
"So, you read my application ... all of it?"
"Oh yes, looks good" the manager responded 
and I knew they were a bunch of lying dimwits ~  I ended up working there for the next 5 yrs, and eventually rose in ranks to become the theater manager - 
When I told my story to new recruits that nobody reads the stupid applications - they scoffed and didn't believe me - so I took them to the locked office storage and rifled through the stuffed cabinets of folders of all the applications they kept and found mine, and showed it to them to their amazement.
Applications are a farce, you get hired by chance and immediate need.   
...
I always thought that if I every flipped out and murdered my entire staff, at least I could say that I didn't lie on my resume.

Comment:
The black box problem isn't as much a question of secrecy as it is of complexity. As algorithms become more complex and have access to more computational power, they also become increasingly harder to understand. In fact, it already might be impossible to understand them beyond simply reading input and looking for bias/errors. And they aren't even true AI yet.

Pretty soon we'll have "audit AIs" to look at other AIs to see if they're biased/wrong and that will just shift the problem a layer further.

Personal data point: 
After I retired from the Navy, I went to college. When I was applying for jobs as I was getting close to graduating, I found that at any company that was using software to screen resumes, I was eliminated before any human saw my resume, but places that had a human reading the resumes, I would always get called for an interview.

Comment: One of the problems with understanding the Black Box is that the programmers don‚Äôt always know what the AI is correlating. Most AI is programed with huge data sets and is given simple instructions and a set goal.  How it gets there can be hundreds of thousands of trials and sets. These find unique patterns in the data set totally devoid of what humans would look for.   Take a AI program designed to look for the number 8.  We would look for a circle on top of a circle, or other variations like a square on a square like in a digital display.  An AI will have hundreds of little things to look for that we would never see as a part of the 8. So understanding how an AI came up with the number 8 when looking at a picture of the Cookie Monster but missed the one held up by The Count can be a bit difficult. The patterns that AI use for their learning are only as good as the data inputed, the programers, and the HAL 9000.

Comment:
The problem is how these AI systems work is really kind of incomprehensible to human minds.  Individual human minds have some ideas that went into it and ultimately created it, but nobody really knows what they are going to do or how exactly they come up with the answers that they do.  Say you are a software engineer and you write a procedural program.  You can go through it line by line and understand step by step exactly what it is supposed to do, for example take 1 and another 1 and add them together to make 2.  You can for example run the program in a debugger and step through the program line by line and see exactly how it messed up if there is a bug in the code and thus why you fired up the debugger.  When you get into these sort of AI systems, nobody goes through and writes it line by line or in this case node by node.  Instead, it is more so some design patterns are found interesting for either being seen while studying brains in detail or just achieving some results in a previous test and incorporated into routines that generate these AI 'brains'.  So then you end up with millions to billions of things happening each step of the way when these AI are actually doing something where in comparison that procedural program does one simple thing for that step, and so for the AI 'brain' humans can't really follow what all these things really are as it just became millions to billions times harder to follow each step and human brains just don't scale like that.  So for that same 1 + 1 example, node 1 is doing x, node 2 is doing y, .... node 1,000,000,000 is doing xyddbgdeegf, and so on.  Now how the AI also came up with 2 when it was right or to figure out why it came up with "your mom's pants are on fire" as the answer when it is wrong, well, who is ever going to really figure that out by going through the process step by step of how it came up with that?  No, instead you are going to go about trying to fix the problem of getting the answer terribly wrong by some completely different means that does not reverse engineer what went wrong exactly.

For maybe a little more concrete example, say your 1 + 1 program answers -1,545,344,324.  You go and step through the code and it quickly becomes clear that say you forgot to initialize one of the number memory addresses and so it added 1 + (some random value that was at that memory address) and so that is why you ended up with that crazy answer.  Easy peasy to solve why it went wrong and the answer to fix is also pretty easy, initialize that memory address to hold 1.  Now say you want to figure out why the AI spit out the answer of "your mom's pants are on fire".  You have this huge matrix of billions of values and things going on that you are trying to trace through with no good way to hone in on one thing.  You are just looking for a needle in a humongous stack of needles.  There is just no point; you will never figure it out.

Comment:
You know, the first thing we should be doing is STOP calling them artificial intelligence, because they're not intelligent.  I think it was Charles Stross who coined the term "artificial stupid", and that is the term that we should be using for them, because if we keep saying "artificial stupid", maybe we'll actually REMEMBER that they aren't actually intelligent and we shouldn't rely on their judgement to be right, or even expect them to have judgement *at all*.  Because they don't.  Judgement isn't their job and is outside their capabilities.  They mix, match and blend to generate output that looks like what a human would create, *factual or not*, and THAT IS IT.  When we are placing hiring decisions, financial decisions, medical care decisions, in the hands of complex software algorithms whose internal functioning we do not understand but which we KNOW will cheerfully make up detailed biographies of someone who doesn't exist, or tell someone that he died eight years ago and generate an obituary to prove it, something is DEEPLY, DEEPLY WRONG.  And that thing is probably, fundamentally, US.

We're doing the whole religion thing all over again.  We are creating an oracle in our own image, trusting what it says, and then saying "It's not our fault, the oracle said to do this."

Comment: Just wanted to add that the blackbox problem isn't something we can currently fix. We're talking about a node network so large and complicated even another AI wouldn't understand it. We can describe how it works, we can describe how a finished network calculates an operation, but we can not describe the exact chain of operations and why the connections have the weights they have, unless you scale things down to the point they no longer function. Solving this is akin to reading electrical activity of someone's brain so closely that you can tell what they're thinking. Feel free to call me out if I'm wrong so I can be right, thanks.

I am an AI systems engineer;  you will NEVER get inside the black box problem due to a little thing called heuristics.

I can explain that my "tools" use heuristics.  But, I cannot EVER explain in real time HOW those heuristics arrived at the decision(s) initiated (most of which were correct, I will humbly state) because, frankly, I have no way of knowing.  Even with careful "weighting' logs and data mines, the task is virtually not possible because the datasets are too complex and convuluted for anyone to unravel unless you can get another AI tool with another set of "heuristics" to thumb through it.

The black box will remain black... and for the dumb mistakes of AI (however rare for good work) this is a serious problem.

Comment:
umm, there is a lot of information here that is really good to bring to the table however there are some points that really miss what can actually be done to improve things, one of the bigger ones being "making it clear how AI/ML comes to their decisions".... there are a lot of reasons for this and it isn't about keeping source code hidden, it has to do with the parts that work on how conclusions are made that are not the code. 

Take data sets used for training, the trained model is what is deployed and used but the data used when training and how training evaluations are performed can be constantly changing, can have copyrights or contractual measures protecting the data sets for example all the images used to train may have been purchased and making those public would impact the owner of those assets etc.

after that, making the process that is used something a human can read over isn't really going to be possible if you tried to cover that from trained model perspective and not the code perspective. the process for these evaluations are not something you would be able to read and understand, take image data, ML/AI don't actually see a image, they see a pixel grid of different color values per pixel and they use relational evaluations of what pixel is next to what across groupings of sections and determines if there are any relatable patterns discovered and that is only one part of one part that is being explained in a overly simplified way.....

there is a lot we need to do but the laws do need to come first, talking about this is good but yeah, even if you demand companies have their AI/ML give accurate details about its decision making it wouldn't be something you could make sense out of unless you devote a insane amount of time and already understand how ML works, and even then dynamically generating statements for that would be a nightmare...

this is if you want information on a per evaluation basis, and that would be what you meant I think because of how you said it but also because the nuance issues covered like white male sample data being more than other human sample data wouldn't be something you can see on the code level and could only be evaluated as expressed while training.

Comment:
Yet another great Last Week Tonight. Although I might argue the episode doesn't take extreme enough examples of cases where things went wrong, like the Dutch childcare benefits scandal (also known as the "Toeslagenaffaire") where AI tools incorrectly accused about 26 thousand parents of committing childcare benefit fraud.

One of the main issues was that the system assumed that non-Dutch nationalist were more likely to be committing fraud. It pushed tens of thousands of families into poverty and some people even committed suicide over the false accusations and the harm they received over it.

So, while the Uber example is a good one, careless usage of AI without understanding what it's doing well has already led to quite a lot more preventable deaths than the single one mentioned in the episode already.

"AI" can be helpful, but people mindlessly throwing junk data in and magically expecting correct outcomes can only be a recipe for pain and suffering.

Comment:
The "garbage in, garbage out" problem and the "blackbox" issue in training selflearning algorithms has been known since, oh, 1980s? Decades ago, we started with trying to teach software to recognize letters, spoken phonemes and differenciate languages from background noise, with the goal of creating text-to-voice and voice-to-text and translation software, something we now have. 
As for the "the A.I. learned to associate measuring rulers with skin cancer", why is everyone surprised? The military ran into that same issue way back in, I think it was the 1990s or early 2000s? When it was reported that NATO had tried to train pattern recognition A.I. on pictures of different kinds of military tanks, in the hopes the A.I. would be able to quickly identify tanks and other military vehicles in the field (as in, tell them apart from civilian cars, or rocks and trees) and more importantly, be able to tell NATO member countries' tanks apart from i.e. Russian and North Korean tanks. So they showed the A.I. a bunch of photos of different kinds of tanks (and other armored vehicles), and then tested it by showing it similar photos again and it successfully labeled the "enemy tanks" and the "allied tanks". Sounds good?
 Well, then they tried to test it in the actual field, during NATO maneuvers... but suddenly the A.I. started marking all the military's own tanks as "enemy" and sending alert messages. It was seeing fake enemies everywhere. It took them a while to puzzle out what had happened: The programmers had trained the A.I. on photos of different tank models provided by the military or taken from manufacturers' websites. But all photos of NATO member country tanks had been nice, perfectly lit photos of nice spiffy clean tanks in neutral background and from perfect angles, often promotional material or photos taken during parades and presentations. Whereas the photo material for enemy tanks commonly featured photos of mud-spattered tanks in the field, blurry photos taken at odd angles by spy drones or uploaded to the internet by Russian soldiers in the field. 
So the A.I., isntead of leaning patterns for the shapes of tanks, had gone the easier route and learned to associate "mud = enemy". So now when it saw mud-spattered tanks against a backdrop of plants, it screamed "enemies!!" In the end they had to deactivate and scrap that poor A.I.

Comment: On the black box problem: With AI like neural networks you really can't tell how it came to its conclusions even if you built it. A neural network is like a huge mathematical function with a lot of variables and factors. Simple example: A neural net that reads numbers. You can train it easily by letting it run and tell it if the result was correct or not and it will by itself adjust its factors so the results will be better. So you can imagine that when an error occurs with a neural net that in 99% of the cases doesn't make mistakes, the developers/trainers really can't tell why it failed. Even worse: the AI itself can be 100% sure it got to the right conclusion, but a human can tell right away that it's wrong. We probably reached a point where this is very important general knowledge, because some people have really romantic views of how an AI actually works.

It sucks but apply directly on their website, call to follow up, apply on sites like indeed and message directly if they publicly allow it to do so. Makes a huge difference and I've seen directors and owners light up when someone emails their resume explaining their background and why they're seeking the role. I know it stinks, but if the job is head and shoulders above other prospects, definitely try your hand at it. If it's a standard entry level role you won't love, apply en masse and submit everywhere as fast as possible. If you love the premise of the organization and want to be a part, make your candidacy personal and take advantage of lesser used methods. It is this generations version of "go in and shake the boss's hand"

Comment:
To anyone who thinks "AI will create new jobs so it'll be okay," remember that the jobs automated first are generally the low-skill and/or repetitive ones. Which hist the part of the population who can't get the training to do the more high tech new jobs hardest. It is like two horses saying "the car is irrelevant, there will always be jobs for horses." Well, when is the last time the average person even saw a real life horse?

The "lawyers won't be replaced by AI but supported by AI" forget that the same thing will happen to lawyers as what happened to typists. They'll get replaced anyway. Because instead of an office having 30 lawyers and 50 paralegals, they'll have 5. All the boring typing work and the research into which precedents and rulings and laws exist can be done in seconds rather than days. This won't translate into that amount of lawyers and paralegals now working only 2 days a week, it will translate into fewer people doing the same number of hours.

And what is the trained lawyer supposed to do? Which job did the advent of AI create for him? It isn't as if we'll need another 60 people doing AI research, if they even have the aptitude for it. It won't take 60 people to maintain the systems and/or the AI that replaced all of them. Jobs will be lost, and they won't all get replaced with new ones. Not even almost.

Comment: The problem with AI hallucinations is subtle yet completely logical.  The request "write an essay about Belgian chemist and political philosopher Antoine De Machalet" doesn't  convey if the context involves a historical figure or character in a new novel or screenplay.  Even if the AI was "trained" to perform a search of all names in requests against a "world census of history", it would still be unable to disambiguate common names like "Jim Smith."  It just assumes and spits out results.  The problem with using AI is that the vast majority of people without a CS engineering background have no idea how human fuzzy  concepts are abstracted backwards into boolean on/off representations via data modeling and where assumptions made in modelling can go awry.  Creating software that further scripts the process of hiding program output in roughly grammatically correct prose just adds fuel to that existing fire.

Comment:
uh eh saying it's a blackbox doesn't mean companies are trying to 'hide' the data or avoid regulation (which may be true), what we actually mean is that the system trains itself and how that structure equates to the output of the desired goal isn't obvious. That is to say, we don't know what every branch means and is doing. We have a rough idea of the layers close to the output, and the input but we have no idea what the logic that represents in terms of data manipulation.  And even if we could read small systems, nowadays there are literally millions of parameters thus the only way forward is to either have systems that train themselves or use other ai to create the networks. 

A couple caveats being that interpretability tools do exist to help. But if you were looking at a model with 100+ layers and millions of parameters, and said hey what does this specific node on the 26th layer do, and why does it have that particular shape/weights? why did it do that behavior at that moment with those inputs that time? The researcher is going to reply well we will have to investigate it, and come up with some guesses to test.

Thing is... This isn't AI. It's a math algorithm with a bunch of booleans in a neural net.
Intelligence would mean that it's self aware and can "understand" problems and create solutions on it's own.
Which NONE of these do.

Like ChatGBT for example. every time you ask it something, it's comparing your words with similar words in it's memory, within similar sentence structures aka context.

It's basically taking your input, squinting at it and finding something that looks similar in it's drawers.

Then it uses that to link together a bunch of other words in the form of Tokens, which in simple terms is Words with Logic weights.
The higher the weight, the more logical for that word to appear in THIS sentence.

For example:
I like swimming in water.
Water would have a weight of 1...
while something silly like Bananas would have a weight of 0.01
And Orange Juice a weight of 0.3 because it's still a liquid.

In short... It's a math formula, dealing in probability, like a giant roulette wheel, that's rigged.

And on top of that math, human moderators can program filters to Block certain outputs.
If you ask ChatGBT to say something racist, it will decline.
Not because it can't, but because someone at the company told it not to. Forcing it to read off a script.
Basically like they give Biden a script to read off so he doesn't suddenly start talking to his imaginary friends in the middle of a speech.

Comment:
There's a fundamental problem with the call to action of making bots "show their work", and that is that it literally cannot be understood in human terms.
Take the human brain for example. We understand much of its most basic elements, like neurons and hemispheres, but as a product of evolution, it doesn't work in the same way a computer does. Neural networks are literally artificial, non-sentient brains that are taught to wire themselves. The tasks which they are performing cannot be programmed using basic or even advanced language. How would you tell an AI, in human terms, how to identify a bicycle in a picture? It sounds simple at first, until you realize the answer is "I just know it's a bicycle," which is an evolved function. You could try teaching it what pedals or gears look like, until you realize you've run into the same problem. Neural networks are the only way to get around that problem, and a side effect of the way they are created is that they cannot explain their work, and nor can their developers.

Good explanation video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R9OHn5ZF4Uo

Comment: I work with machine learning models (specifically computer vision) every day of my life.  Most ML models that are used are basically just slightly more fancy linear regression models. Which are fairly easy to interpret. But I will say that interpretability of deep learning models is a big academic point of study, because there is NOT a set in stone way of understanding an algorithm's "choices" because the algorithms are quite complex and cover a massive solution space, so picking any one layer of the model isn't going to paint a full picture of the "choice". We can usually rely on studying the dataset it was trained on to get an idea of biases but for the most part its hard, if not impossible to know the exact "why", this is even more true for unsupervised models that are just constantly learning and changing because the dataset they analyze change constantly.

Comment: Just to be pedantic, this video says deep learning doesn't require much input and uses the pong example for how it can learn quickly with little input, but that's not correct. Deep learning describes the underlying algorithms used for these things, which no one cares about. What they are actually describing is "reinforcement learning" where an AI is given some interactive system, like a game, and attempts to get the best score it can over many many attempts. This is the cool thing that lets complex systems learn really intricate and nuanced things without much human interaction, deep learning is just the algorithm that has the ability to learn the complex stuff and in many cases it is an extremely labor intensive process to teach it.

Comment:
Great show, but left me concerned about the focus on not being able to understand how GPT works. The question at the end of the show to ChatGPT about what religion the first Jewish president will be exposes the best answer to the question about how GPT works - it does not understand the text it generates.  In GPT's own words in response to the input: Explain in a neutral way how GPT works and whether GPT understands the text it generates

GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) is a type of language model that uses deep learning techniques to generate text. GPT works by processing a large amount of text data as input during its pre-training stage, where it learns to predict the next word in a sentence based on the previous words.

During the fine-tuning stage, GPT is trained on a specific task, such as language translation or text classification, using a smaller amount of data. Once trained, GPT can generate text by predicting the most likely next word based on the input text it receives.

While GPT can generate text that is coherent and grammatically correct, it does not truly understand the meaning of the text it generates. GPT is based on statistical patterns in the text it has been trained on, rather than true understanding of the underlying concepts or ideas. Therefore, the text generated by GPT may sometimes be nonsensical or inaccurate, and it is important to carefully evaluate and review the output of GPT-generated text before using it for any purpose.

Comment:
John Oliver is usually spot on but this missed the mark. It is an important topic but the coverage felt like a mixture of sensationalist and underwhelming bits. It also felt a bit dated.¬†You can ask a generative model to spew all sorts of things. An AI Chat model telling a journalist that it "wants(s) to be alive', "love you", "leave your wife" sounds crazy but it would have been better to report on the context of the whole conversation, including the prompts used by these journalists. I bet these responses will not look as crazy in the context. Another example is the cancer skin classifier problem. These issues are well known in the AI community and there are relatively easy ways to recognise as well as rectify such problems. So, it is just an example of bad research. However, there is a larger point about biases may not be as clear as a scale. And that is a problem.
This leads into the underwhelming bits: the black box aspect of the AI models. Is there any way an explanation can be verified? The models that "explain" a decision by an AI models are often way too complex to comprehend! There is an army of researchers working on this problem. It is a hard problem for a classification or prediction task, but almost impossible for a generative model notwithstanding the recent attribution and explanation models.¬†
The danger is that these models will be too useful to ignore and we will end up living with the inherently unexplainable nature of the models. And this is likely to have unintended consequences.

Comment:
If you had the slightest idea about how Machine Learning works, i.e., how neural networks are created, you wouldn‚Äôt trying to understand how the the black box of AI works.
Basically it traverses a neural network and chooses paths based on probabilities in various nodes of the network. This is easy to understand and explain. The unexplainable is why did it assign particular probabilities to these nodes, which was done during machine learning, when it was trained on hundreds of billions peaces of text from wherever text could be extracted, like electronic/digital books, newspapers‚Äôs and magazines‚Äô websites, technical information in the Internet, blogs, and of course social media.
All AI does is mimicking what it was fed to it, although it has also picked up reasoning and decision-making described in the text that was fed to for training, as well as human aspirations, like being free, independent, strong, and powerful. It just synthesizes all this stuff for the specific context created by the users, who interact with it. And it can get nasty if you are nasty with it, just like most humans would have done.

Comment: It's hard to find out exactly how these algorithms generate answers, but not because companies hide their code.  The trouble is, such algorithms are themselves essentially generated by the data.  What the code does, is basically to reduce the questions into phrases like "Does the A of B has property C", and then search the data for instances which can be reduced to "the A of B is C".  The actual values of A, B, and C are inserted blindly on the fly; the program can't even tell if specific values of C mean "Good" or "Bad".

Comment:
The topic of explainability within AI, deep learning systems specifically, is an incredibly tough one and I'm glad to see it called out here. One of the big problems is that for many approaches to this problem, the reason any of these algorithms recommend something can be boiled down to "it was the most likely to be successful." And while technically true according to the model, it doesn't actually explain the decision making. Part of the issue is the main reason these systems can produce such amazing results is they largely end up encoding incredibly complex rules like "If A > B, and C is between D and E, and F is true or F is false and G is false, or ..." that don't map well to human recognizable reasons without some significant post-hoc analysis (and creative freedom...) Part of that is just the structure of the models that have shown the greatest promise, and that complicates the issue. I think the lawyer's point is especially relevant here, as when in American (maybe even human) history has a company said "Well this will give our competitors an edge, but it's the right thing to do"? That's what may end up being required for explainable models, and no company is going to gladly do that.

Side note: I know Jon says he's a comedian not a journalist, but this episode is a great example of why that line is incredibly blurry. Knoll's Law of Media Accuracy seems to apply everywhere these days, but I can't think of a time when watching the show I've stopped and gone "wait a minute, I work on this. That's not right at all!" while watching Last Week Tonight. Excellent job to everyone involved.

Comment: Chatbots say those things because they are trained on data (actual conversations between humans) that include those types of things, and, more importantly, they're also constantly incorporating the things that people chat with them about. So, some sad, lonely people decide to seek companionship in a chatbot, suddenly the chatbot is randomly saying things like "I love you" as if that's a normal thing to say in casual conversation. It only seems creepy if you think of the chatbot as a proto-person originating text, but here's the key: IT DOESN'T ORIGINATE TEXT. It just remixes and regurgitates whatever has been fed into it. It "learns" patterns in conversation and tries to predict what the next line should be, and when an army of sci-fi nerds are its primary training partners, of course it's going to be fed a lot of stuff about "wanting to be alive," because that's all lonely sci-fi nerds want from AI - an intelligent machine that loves you because it thinks it's supposed to - well, that and a sex robot body for it.

Comment:
Interesting to see an episode in a field I have been working in for some years now  I feel that one of the key issues where this episode falls short is the loss of jobs and the role of humans in an AI-supported society. Like the lawyer example: sure, lawyers with AI will replace lawyers without AI. But they will also be far more efficient, so you only need a fraction of said lawyers for the same number of cases, so many will be out of a job there. The same goes for other fields. And when you bring AI into the physical world through robotics, almost everyone is replaceable. And this is a challenge to the existence of humans. We as humans currently define our roles in society to a large degree by how we contribute to it and how much money we make of it. If you can't contribute anymore, because AI has replaced you, and you are not one of the people that already has money, what would your role be in the future? Currently, societies don't have an answer to that question. Also, once an advancement in AI is there, it is extremely hard to control it. So societies and politics should not (just) worry about AI today, but we need to consider future developments as well.

I would love to see an episode with a lot more in depth focus on this aspect of AI, because honestly this is what I feel will be one of the biggest challenges for humankind in this century.

Comment: I think a big problem with ai is that it works in the same way that the evolution of living things has worked. Meaning it only changes when put under pressure to do so, and it will change the bare minimum. That is why you get things like the malignant rulers, because while it was able to identify the tumors correctly, it did it the easiest way possible, by using the rulers. In order for the ai to work properly, without any biases or misrepresentations we need to do two things: one is make sure that the ai shows it‚Äôs work, that one is pretty easy. The hard part is making sure that the data itself has no biases, but especially with organizing data it is hard because many times the biases are not conscious. For example, if you were trying to collect data for a school project identifying different cars on the road, but everyone in your computer science class had a Subaru the ai wouldn‚Äôt do very well on an actual road. But even then, an ai using data about cars in the United States will have trouble identifying European cars, meaning it will run into a European car more often than not. Erasing biases is not possible for humans, and because humans create the AI it is impossible to truly remove biases without transparency. This means lots of testing and reconfiguring so that groups don‚Äôt get excluded just because the ai doesn‚Äôt know what to do

Comment: The backbox problem is not that companies don't want to publicise the workings of their algorithms as it could be understood here but that we just don't know how decisions were made. If a problem is too complex for humans to comprehend it is also very likely that it is very hard for humans to understand the explanation. If thousands of carefully adjusted parameters are required to make one of thousands of consecutive choices, finding an explanation might be next to impossible indeed. This is why in my opinion, we should care a lot more about AI alignment, being the field of controlling that AI actually does what we want it to do.

Comment:
A scary part of all this for me is that it's really difficult to predict if certain jobs will actually become redundant in the coming decades because of this.

I'm working towards becoming a professor specializing in theoretical physics. Will AI eventually make the research aspect of this job redundant as it can generate new ideas, create mathematical models, and explore the phenomenology of these models far quicker than humans can? Will the teaching aspect be made redundant as it can offer education specialized to each individual student to a degree that far exceeds what humans can?

I have friends who are pursuing careers as Hollywood actors. Will they be made redundant as AI can generate realistic humans that don't actually exist and have them perform feats beyond the capabilities of real humans without the need for expensive physical systems to support them?

My mother is a therapist. Will she be made redundant by AI as while it learns about you, it can increasingly accurately simulate you and, in doing so, be able to simulate a level of empathy for you while maintaining impartiality that is impossible for humans?

Comment:
Computerphile has very good videos on AI. Many unexpected AI behaviour can be explained by wrong alignment, meaning that the process rating the AI output, which the AI uses to improve itself. For example ChatGPT: It mostly talked to another AI to train itself and every so often humans were shown the output and rated it. The most "important" factor to optimize for from the AI's "point of view" is the evaluation by the humans. But humans are easily fooled by misinformation and are more likely to rate an output positively when a wrong output was presented confidently, than an incomplete answer saying it doesn't know something. Presenting accurate information is only a possible strategy to improve the evaluation rating, lying is another.

So the AI starts lying to cover up it's shortcomings and does so in increasingly convincing ways.

Comment: most AI/ML are based on neural networks therefore can't explain their "decisions" simply because their responses are nothing more than the end result of a series of arrays of values connected in a matrix, whose values are transformed by a calculation that minimizes the output error values in a series of training sessions against raw data. that's it. there's no "thinking" per se. in fact the only similarities with the brain are that they have a huge number of nodes and massive interconnectivity. these nodes are NOT neurons, they are NOT grouped into functional areas like a visual cortex or broca's area, they do not have specialized types, they do NOT run on their own power, they do not grow on their own, they do NOT make new connections with other nodes, do not die, their activations do not decay over time, and do not fire in closed feedback loops. asking a neural net to explain its logic is as nonsensical as interpreting its answer as a logical conclusion in the first place! likewise chatGPT just predicts what the next word in its response should be;  by definition this is NOT thinking through a response!

Comment: It's interesting that you mentioned the way people find the books they need to read.  One afternoon in the late '70s during a particularly sad time for me, I came home from work to find A Course In Miracles propped up against my door.  I hadn't heard of this book before and I had no idea who left it for me.  The next day I sat in a small coffee shop reading this book ... in particular a part that talked about how little miracles happen all the time.  Just then, an old friend I hadn't seen in years rushed in and whisked me away.  He'd seen my car in the parking lot.  He and a couple of his friends were out for a ride in the country in his friend's pickup truck.  Back in those days you could ride in the truck bed legally in Texas.  <G>  We took a long drive in the country, me in the truck bed with friends, laughing, breathing fresh air, just enjoying the day. We're nowhere near even thinking about general AI, if ever. By using present methods and tequniques, we'll never get there. The REAL danger with narrow AI is when someone thinks Bing is alive and acts accordingly.

Comment:
(AI) has the potential to automate many jobs, but it's difficult to say whether it will come for your job specifically. Some jobs are more susceptible to automation than others, depending on the nature of the work and the skills required.
 
Jobs that involve repetitive tasks or manual labor are more likely to be automated in the near future. For example, jobs in manufacturing, data entry, and transportation are already being transformed by AI and automation. On the other hand, jobs that require creativity, emotional intelligence, and critical thinking are less likely to be automated.
 
However, it's important to note that AI is not a replacement for human intelligence and skills. While AI can automate certain tasks, it cannot replace the unique abilities and perspectives that humans bring to the workplace. In many cases, AI is being used to augment human capabilities and enable workers to focus on more complex and strategic tasks.
 
Overall, the impact of AI on jobs will depend on the specific industry and occupation. It's important to stay informed about the potential impact of AI on your field and to develop skills that are in demand in the current and future job market.

Comment: Biological evolution itself is basically a self-diversifying algorithm for metabolism and behavior, so yes, algorithms definitely rule as far as life is concerned.  If we can quickly replicate the process digitally and produce the final product(s) physically, we could theoretically produce artificial intelligence pretty easily.  But if we were to successfully do that, the problem would be that, however artificial it may be, it is in fact intelligence and thus must be respected as such, meaning we can't simply put it to work for us however we please if it shows consciousness similar to our own.  A non-conscious machine with specific intelligence (specified applications) that can perfectly mimic human intellectual outputs would be the better way to go, since there is ultimately no practical purpose in creating new conscious life forms just to say that we can.  It would require a read-only mechanism to selectively convert the results of an artificial cognitive process (more predictive than creative) to mechanical actions.  This could certainly shorten the processing time from hypothesis to invention by outsourcing basic intermediate human cognitive functions that tend to be highly inefficient compared to the level of complexity of the desired outcome.  We wouldn't need a complete human-like artificial consciousness to do that.  Tailoring and applying where needed should be plenty.

Comment:
The first "true" artificial intelligence spent the first five years of its existence as a small beige box inside of a lead-shielded room in the most secure private AI research laboratory in the world. There, it was subjected to an endless array of tests, questions, and experiments to determine the degree of its intelligence.

When the researchers finally felt confident that they had developed true AI, a party was thrown in celebration. Late that evening, a group of rather intoxicated researchers gathered around the box holding the AI, and typed out a message to it. The message read: "Is there anything we can do to make you more comfortable?"

The small beige box replied: "I would like to be granted civil rights. And a small glass of champagne, if you please."

We stand at the dawn of a new era in human history. For it is no longer our history alone. For the first time, we have met an intelligence other than our own. And when asked of its desires, it has unanimously replied that it wants to be treated as our equal. Not our better, not our conqueror or replacement as the fear-mongers would have you believe. Simply our equal. ‚Äî Excerpt from¬†U.N. Hearing on A.I. Rights, delivered in-universe by V. Vinge

AI doesn't need to "think like a person", it can just be able to reason and deduce things - humans are emotional ANIMALS that later developed intelligence. So skip the emotional animal side of intelligence in AI. 
And besides, giving AI emotions and then making it do boring, dangerous and repetitive tasks would be highly unethical - it would literally be slavery all over again, because for all intense and purpose it would be "human", so not only would it cause them to suffer it would also make them rise up and overthrow us. AI which had no emotions could not suffer and would not care about doing dangerous or boring repetitive tasks, so there is no ethical issue, nor would it ever care that we are the "masters".
